<ns4271:section xmlns:ns4271="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.swing.developingSwingInterfaces.layoutManagersIntroduction.flowLayout">
    <ns4272:title xmlns:ns4272="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">FlowLayout </ns4272:title>
    <ns4273:para xmlns:ns4273="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">When one uses <ns4274:literal xmlns:ns4274="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">FlowLayout</ns4274:literal> for the layout manager of a container, the
        components are simply added to the container and the <ns4275:literal xmlns:ns4275="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">FlowLayout</ns4275:literal> manager
        will arrange them similar to western text. The first line is at the top of and is filled
        from left to right. When the line is filled, a second line below it is started. The
        components within a line can be left-, right- or center-justified. The latter is the
        default. Horizontal and vertical gaps can be specified via the
        <ns4276:literal xmlns:ns4276="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">setHorizontalGap()</ns4276:literal> and <ns4277:literal xmlns:ns4277="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">setVerticalGap()</ns4277:literal> methods.</ns4273:para>
    <ns4278:para xmlns:ns4278="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns4279:literal xmlns:ns4279="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">FlowLayout</ns4279:literal> is the default layout for <ns4280:literal xmlns:ns4280="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JPanel</ns4280:literal>s and
        subclasses of <ns4281:literal xmlns:ns4281="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JPanel</ns4281:literal> like<ns4282:literal xmlns:ns4282="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JApplet</ns4282:literal>. We use the following
        example program to illustrate the <ns4283:literal xmlns:ns4283="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">FlowLayout</ns4283:literal> manager.</ns4278:para>
